It’s National #MeatballDay so Blakely and I decided to celebrate by making Meatball Sliders using @armaninofoods #meatballs and let me tell yall, these are a must-try!

Here’s what you’ll need: 

-24 Meatballs : We used #Armanino & you can find those here: https://armaninofoods.com/where-to-buy/

- 24 Kings Hawaiian Rolls (2 12pk packages)

- 1 Cup Marinara Sauce

- 1 Cup Mozzarella Cheese

- ½ Cup Parmesan Cheese

Garlic Butter: 

- 1/4 cup butter softened 

- 2 tbsp fresh parsley chopped

- 1/2 tsp dried basil

- 1/4 tsp dried thyme

- 1/4 tsp kosher salt

- 1/2 tsp garlic paste

Directions: 

1. Preheat the oven to 375˚F.
2. Make the garlic butter by combining all of the ingredients.
3. Arrange the rolls in a 9×13” pan so that they fit snugly or 2 smaller pans. 
4. Use a serrated knife to cut a hole out of the middle of each roll. 
5. Brush the tops and side the hole with the garlic butter mixture evenly. 
6. Bake for 6-8 minutes to melt the butter and toast the rolls. Then remove from oven.
7. Mix the mozzarella and parmesan cheese. 
8. Use half the cheese to place a small amount in each of the holes in the rolls. 
9. Stuff a meatball into the hole on top of the cheese, then top the meatball with a dollop of sauce. 
10. Sprinkle the remaining half of the cheese over the top of the sandwiches.
11. Bake for 20-25 minutes or until the meatballs are hot and the cheese is melted
12. Enjoy!

Mother’s Day feels a little extra special this year as my mom is on the victorious side of her year long battle with cancer.
.
5 months of chemo.
1 major surgery + another after a complication.
Then 2+ months of daily radiation; fortunately receiving some of the best treatment in the country but by living temporarily in Houston.
All of this on top of so many tests, scans, appts and medications in between…
It was a really tough year for my mom, but she damn sure made the most of it.
She worked through most of her treatment. 
Never missed an OU home game or tailgate. 
Spent a lot of time with her kids and dogs.
And still traveled to see her granddaughter whenever possible. 
She never stopped being “mom” or “grandma”. Because neither are a role she plays, they’re just who she is. 
.
She is selfless, she is kind, she is fun, she is forgiving, she is supportive, she is oh so very patient and so many other wonderful things. All qualities I truly admire and try to emulate in myself as a mom. Her natural maternal ways inspire me every day to be at least half the mom she is. If I can accomplish that, I’d say I’ll be doing alright. 🫶🏼
.
She will continue to be on some not very fun medication for the foreseeable future as cancer is an unpredictable disease. But for now, we celebrate her health and Jesus’ healing hands leading her body to victory! 🙌 
Happy Mother’s Day, mom. 
I’m just so happy you’re here. 
Thank you for fighting so hard and for being the best mom and grandma out there. 🩷
We love you more than words can even describe! 
.
A few side notes:
*This was her song I prayed, cried and sang over her all year long. I still can’t listen to it without tearing up. 😭
**A very frequently asked question: she cold capped during chemo so she was able to keep a lot of her hair and ended up not needing her wig.

I’ve got peace that makes no sense.“ I bit my tongue, smiled at B and let her continue on. 
My house may be chaotic, but I can still be joyful. 
It may not make any sense, but I can be at peace knowing that my children are taken care of and loved. Even if my house doesn’t always reflect that peace. 
“When everything around me is shaking, I’ve never been more glad.”

For someone who is Type A like me, disorder can disrupt my entire day. So I’m learning to clean up and control what I can, but also to take a deep breath and still be a patient mom when I can’t keep up. 
“So I won’t be going under. I’m not held by my own strength. Cuz I built my life on Jesus. He’s never let me down. He’s faithful through every season.
So why would He fail now? He won’t.”
Leaning not on my own strength is what sustains me. 

This isn’t the first busy season of my life and it won’t be my last. This might be the most fleeting and precious one though. And I don’t want to spend the majority of it stressing about the mess.
It all eventually gets cleaned up.

We’ve come a long way in our 9 years of working in the online marketing world, with the last 6 of those being in the e-commerce & digital selling space. 
We’ve put ourselves out there, looked silly, made mistakes and took bold messy action. We haven’t always got it right, but the knowledge and success we’ve gained along the way has set us apart because we just took the first step. We didn’t wait until we were great at something before started. We. Just. Started.

What first step do you need take? 
We’d love to help you do it. 🫶

Explaining everything in a little more detail: 

1. If we can’t do something or give her what she needs in that moment because we are busy with the baby, we don’t blame the baby. Instead of “I can’t right now, I’m feeding your sister.” We say something like, “I will help you in 5 minutes, do you want to come sit by me or play while you wait?”

2. Kids tend to regress to baby like tendencies when a new sibling is born. Instead of telling them, “stop acting like a baby.” We let her do some baby-ish things if she wants. If she wants to be held or rocked or picked up and we have free hands to do so, we do. The more we have allowed her to just go through this phase, the less “baby-ing” she has needed. Let them be little. 

3. We over praise little things right now and thank her when she’s helpful. We thank her for her kindness, patience and gentleness with her sister. The more we thank her, the more she wants to do those things!

4. When a child is used to only having mom or dad’s attention, it can be hard to share it with a new sibling. Any time we can run an errand or go to the park with just her, we do. And she LOVES it. It can be the littlest thing but her “just mommy and Blakely” outings really fill her cup. Same with grocery store runs or park dates with daddy.

5. Kids usually love to help and so we have given her jobs since we brought the baby home. She is now the official diaper and wipes fetcher. Because of this, she’s proud to help and loves her job of being a big sister. She actually gets upset if we forget to ask her first for help lol.

6. Babies are the ones being fought over when they’re born. You may not realize it, but toddlers pick up on this. My husband and I make it a point to sometimes fight over who gets to put our toddler to bed, who gets to snuggle her or hold her hand. And she beams from ear to ear when we do this. She thinks it’s the funniest, most special thing.
